{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11864"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.04,0.46,0.02,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63519"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26803"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after getting hit in the eye from a nail while hammering. The nail head broke off and hit his right eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most consistent with a penetrating globe injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Large corneal abrasion","Traumatic cataract","Positive Seidel test","Vertical lid laceration","Traumatic hyphema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERuling out penetrating globe injury is the number one priority when assessing a case of ocular trauma. Examination could be difficult due to the limited access to necessary equipment, decreased cooperation of the patient, or the presence of other facial/body trauma. Therefore it is crucial to quickly and reliably identify a penetrating globe injury if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the easiest ways of detecting ocular trauma is applying Fluorescein drops in the injured eye, then observing the suspected wound site for a leak or gush of fluid under cobalt blue filter. The leaking fluid will dilute the dye and appear as a blue stream of fluid on a background of green dye. If a leak was observed this is considered a \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003ESeidel test\u003C/strong\u003E that signifies a full thickness wound that usually requires surgical repair. It should be noted that in some cases the test might be negative if the wound is small and self-sealed. The test will also be negative in cases of a partial thickness wound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll other options \u003C/strong\u003Emay be seen in cases of trauma but do not on their own indicate a penetrating globe injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A positive Seidel test indicates the presence of penetrating globe injury.","Penetrating globe injury is highly probable in cases of high-velocity ballistic injury.","Immediate ophthalmology consultation is necessary for suspected penetrating globe injuries."],"references":["Syed, Z.A. 2022. Seidel Test - EyeWiki. [online] eyewiki.aao.org. Available at: https://eyewiki.aao.org/Seidel_Test.","Blair K, Alhadi SA, Czyz CN. Globe Rupture. 2024 Mar 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31869101. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31869101/","Heath Jeffery RC, Dobes J, Chen FK. Eye injuries: Understanding ocular trauma. Aust J Gen Pract. 2022 Jul;51(7):476-482. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-03-21-5921. PMID: 35773155. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35773155/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:38:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T16:44:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/